metadata.name: Consequence Broadcast [Speed Run] #137
metadata.description:
a.k.a. Reaction Diffusion. The canvas is a grid of cells, each containing some amount of A and some amount of B. Every step, A and B react with each other and diffuse into neighbouring cells. The amounts of diffusion and reaction have different settings, which can vary across the canvas or over time. Then, cool things happen with colours. 

This is an experimental project, created as part of a Speed Run over ~37 hours in one weekend (I did also sleep and eat in that time. I even went for a walk. Go me). 
- It requires WEBGL2 and is GPU intensive. 
- There may be slight discrepancies in the patterns on different devices, due to rounding. 

Big thanks to everyone who followed along/offered advice and especially to Piter Pasma who helped me out with the noise dithering code that took everything to the next dimension.

Press P to pause.
Press 1-5 to alter speed.

metadata.name: Bento Boxes #255
metadata.description:
Everybody needs a bento box in the cryptowinter.
The project calls for an adopted nostalgia of little kids that has been handed bento box by their parents before school— a little moment of protected comfort before heading out for an adventure.

• • •

The first collaboration project of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. A work based on MEK.txt’s “The Bento Boxes” and IceRain’s excellent codes, Bento Boxes aims to be a fun visual and code exploration project on the generative art corridor. Pure code, no libraries.

Bento Boxes deconstructed the visual system on MEK.txt's artwork, titled almost similarly, “The Bento Boxes”. Rebuilt it from scratch with codes, adding variants of colours and shapes— without losing the strong characteristics of the base artwork.

metadata.name: Ghrian #87
metadata.description:
Dutch auction (13/11/9/6/3), with price decreasing every 10 minutes after the start of the auction until 9 tez. Price will then decrease to 6 tez after 2 hours, then to 3 after 12 hours.

A selection of 33 different palettes.

The brush draw is determined by angles, shapes, randomly chosen overdraws, brush sizes and widths, among other things.

- Left arrow = draw in 2125x1375
- Right arrow = draw in 11x17 landscape mode fit to screen height
- Up arrow = draw in 1375x2125
- Down arrow = draw in 11x17 portrait mode fit to screen width
- Enter = draw in full window
- Tab = draw in 1400x1400
- Shift = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides
- Alt = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides (default pixel density)
- Left mouse click = save as a png

Pixel density is set to 2 for all of the options above unless noted otherwise.

Please note that the drawing can take quite a while to run, especially in the full screen modes.

See thread below for additional details:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1492619586931413000?s=20&t=N8joIBuTNzYYjmcBex0QJQ

metadata.name: Backyard #47
metadata.description:
The house I lived in when I was young was a house with a small backyard with brick walls. I often imagined it in the backyard at the time.
If I grow up and have my own house later, I want to live in a house with a backyard with a dense nature and a view of a vast mountain.
Although I haven't achieved the imagination that I did when I was young yet. I'm so happy because I think it came true in the world of generative art.
I hope you have the backyard that you imagine.

--

Features:
 - Canvas: vertical / horizontal
 - Palette: black / red / green / purple / yellow / blue
 - Highlighted object: tree / flowers / brickwall
 - MountainType: standard / sharp
 - Tree: true / false
 - Flowers: true / false
 - Stars: true / false
 - Fog: true / false
 - Brickwall: true / false
 - Sun or Moon: true / false / supersize
 - After the rain: true / false

--

Press "s" in live mode to download the rendered image as a png file. (2000 x 3000 for vertical, 3000 x 1500 for horizontal)

Made with p5js and passion
By thion, September 2023

metadata.name: Scaffold #238
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

An endless row of them making up each life. Some poignant, some inspiring, some grievous, some affirming - but most of them a tad boring, a bit generic, almost forgettable like bland fabric.
